<TABLE WIDTH="100%" CELLPADDING=5 CELLSPACING=0>
<TR><TD BGCOLOR="FF00FF" COLSPAN=2><FONT COLOR="FFFFFF" SIZE=+2><B>DBS:  Assessment of the Marketplace</B> <FONT SIZE=-1>(CT8)</FONT></TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD VALIGN=TOP WIDTH="10%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD>

	<FONT SIZE=>Moderator(s): <B>Bob Scherman, Satellite Business News</B></FONT>



	<FONT SIZE=+1>Panelist(s): <B>Eddy Hartenstein,  DirectTV; Mike Schroeder,  Consumer Satellite Systems; Daniel O'Brien,  Primestar Partners LP; Charles Ergen,  Echostar Communications; Stan Hubbard,  USSB</B></FONT>


<P>
1997 was another exciting and eventful year for the satellite TV industry.  The industry continued its unprecedented growth and faced a number of new challenges.  As satellite TV enters a new year, the industry's key leaders will take a look back at last year's biggest news and market developments, with an eye on forecasting what change is in store for 1998.  Will the industry's unbelievable growth continue on the same pace? How many new hardware companies will enter the fray? Will Rupert Murdoch finally be part of a U.S.  DBS service? Will Washington shape the satellite TV landscape as much as the industry does? And with competition heating up and hardware prices continuing to come down, how can retailers prosper in the year ahead?

</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>

